-------------------------- Zubov's Boot Sector (ZBS) --------------------------

Zubov's Boot Sector (ZBS) is a collection of small boot sector programs that
fit in a single sector (512 bytes) and written in NASM assembly language
for Intel 8086-compatible CPUs, utilizing IBM PC-compatible BIOS interrupts.

ZBS allows you to easily boot your low-level programs just by copying them
to the filesystem root.

Each program performs the following:
  1. Relocates itself from the default boot address (0x7C00) to the lowest
     possible (0x500, right above the IVT and BDA).
  2. Loads the specified file from the filesystem root to the specified
     segment:offset.
  3. Jumps to the specified segment:offset.

Each program supports both CHS and LBA addressing methods.

------------------------------ How to set up ZBS ------------------------------

To apply a boot sector program to your media run:

    ./apply-zbs.sh <target> <filesystem> <offset> <load_filename>
                   <load_to_seg:off> <jump_to_seg:off>

For example, to apply ZBS to a FAT16 partition, first sector of which
is located in the 64th sector of /dev/fda, so that it loads KERNEL.BIN
to 0x0000:0x1000 and jumps to 0x0100:0x0100, run:

    ./apply-zbs.sh /dev/fda FAT16 63 KERNEL.BIN 0x0000:0x1000 0x0100:0x0100

